    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-05-06T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-05-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="1849"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1849">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 831.55/3.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to Minister
                            <persName type="to">McGoodwin</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 48.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-05-06">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 6, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Department has received your unnumbered
                    despatch of the 11th ultimo further discussing the decree issued by the
                    Government of Venezuela under date of January 21, 1914, requiring that
                    foreigners entering Venezuela must present “certificates of good conduct” and
                    “documents attesting their personal status.”</p>
                <p>You will, of course, promptly inform the Department of any specific instance
                    wherein the Government of Venezuela attempts to enforce as against American
                    citizens the requirements mentioned, and you will make appropriate protest
                    against any such attempt which shall be made known to you unless there appear to
                    be good reasons to the contrary.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>For the Secretary of State: <lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
